**How it works**
- Checks `localStorage` on load; if “light”, applies that class.  
- When the ☀️/🌙 button is pressed, toggles the class and writes the new value back.  
- Entire file stays under a few kilobytes and runs anywhere without dependencies.

Here’s a small **“enhancement block”** you can paste at the end of your current file — just before `</style>` or inside a separate CSS/JS section. It adds:

- automatic light/dark detection (respects OS preference)  
- reduced‑motion preference support  
- a light print theme.

Everything is compact and self‑contained.

```html
<!-- ✳️ Drop‑in Enhancement Block -->

<style>
/* --- Accessibility & Print Enhancements --- */

/* Use system color scheme if nothing saved yet */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: light) {
  body:not(.light):not(.dark-toggle-set) {
    background: var(--bg-light);
    color: var(--text-dark);
  }
}

/* Respect user's reduced‑motion setting */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * {
    animation-duration: 0s !important;
    transition: none !important;
  }
}

/* Print‑friendly version: light background, dark text */
@media print {
  body {
    background: #fff !important;
    color: #000 !important;
  }
  .toggle { display: none !important; }
  a { color: #000 !important; text-decoration: underline; }
}
</style>

<script>
/* --- Script hook for system/print handling --- */
(function(){
  // Flag theme as manually toggled when user clicks button
  const toggleBtn = document.querySelector('.toggle');
  if(toggleBtn){
    toggleBtn.addEventListener('click',()=>{
      document.body.classList.add('dark-toggle-set');
    });
  }

  // Apply system preference on first load when no local value
  if(!localStorage.getItem('theme')){
    if(window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: light)').matches){
      document.body.classList.add('light');
    }
  }
})();
</script>
<!-- End Enhancement Block -->
```

**How to use**
1. Paste the `<style>…</style>` and `<script>…</script>` chunk into your file under or after your main styles.  
2. No edits needed elsewhere—your existing toggle and saved preference logic remain intact.  
3. The `dark-toggle-set` class ensures that once a user manually toggles, the automatic setting stops overriding their choice.

Now you can keep the basic page ultra‑light but add these accessibility improvements whenever it fits your training or internal‑tool environment.
